  "text": "Lactoferrin plays a key role in the defense mechanisms of the mammary gland, contributing to the prevention of infectious microbiological diseases . Therefore, the health status of a cow is a very important factor influencing the concentrations of lactoferrin in milk secretions. [CITATION_1] induced E. coli infection in bovine mammary gland, which resulted in a 30-fold increase in the concentrations of lactoferrin in mammary secretion by 90 h post inoculation. Furthermore, they observed that during acute mastitis, lactoferrin concentrations in the milk increased up to 30-fold with the highest production in the infected quarter.",
